-- allium: 3
-- turbo_kv_asymmetric.allium

-- Scope: asymmetric bit allocation for keys and values in the
-- KV cache. Keys and values have different roles in attention,
-- and community measurement consistently shows that values
-- tolerate more aggressive quantisation than keys. Composes on
-- top of the core TurboQuant specs (turbo-kv-4b.allium,
-- turbo-kv-3b.allium).
--
-- Citable sources:
--
--   [PAPER]       Zandieh et al., arxiv 2504.19874. Paper §4
--                 discusses bit-allocation trade-offs between K
--                 and V at the generic vector-quantisation level.
--                 Paper does not validate on specific LLM
--                 attention heads, but the framework allows
--                 different bit-widths per-tensor.
--
--   [TONBI-V3]    tonbistudio/turboquant-pytorch compressors_v3.py.
--                 Class TurboQuantV3 constructor:
--                     def __init__(self, ..., key_bits=4,
--                                  value_bits=2, ...)
--                 Default configuration is asymmetric K=4, V=2.
--                 README measured results (Llama 3.2 needle test,
--                 4K context):
--                   K6/V4 rw=128:  EXACT  (~1.6x compression)
--                   K8/V4 rw=128:  EXACT
--                   K4/V4 rw=128:  PARTIAL ("AURORA7749" — drops
--                                  the hyphen)
--                 8K attention score accuracy:
--                   V3 K4/V2 + protected layers:
--                      cosine 0.9997, 99% top-1 agreement,
--                      3.6x compression
--                 Community finding the V3 compressors_v3.py file
--                 docstring cites: "scos-lab: MSE > QJL for
--                 attention, K/V norm asymmetry… 0xSero:
--                 asymmetric K=3/V=2 on production vLLM".
--
--   [QUANT.CPP]   Does NOT implement asymmetric K/V. Our
--                 llama.cpp port inherits this: K and V share the
--                 same ggml type (TURBO_KV_4B), therefore the
--                 same bit-width. Adopting asymmetric requires
--                 at minimum a second ggml type (e.g.
--                 TURBO_V_3B for value-side 3-bit) or a per-
--                 tensor bit-width override.
--
-- Goal: specify a per-tensor bit-width configuration so that
-- keys and values can be quantised at different precisions, and
-- expose the trade-off measurements so deployers can pick the
-- K/V pair that fits their quality × memory budget.
--
-- Includes: key_bits / value_bits config separation, per-tensor
-- codebook binding, the measurement matrix from [TONBI-V3] for
-- picking defaults.
-- Excludes: layer-adaptive (separate spec), residual window
-- (separate spec), outlier handling (separate spec).

-- ============================================================
-- External entities
-- ============================================================

external entity Tensor {
    data: Set<Decimal>
    count: Integer
}

external entity QuantizedHead {
    norm: Decimal
    inv_std: Decimal
    indices: Set<Integer>
}

-- ============================================================
-- Config
-- ============================================================

config {
    -- Key-tensor bit-width. [TONBI-V3] defaults to 4; measurement
    -- supports K ∈ {3, 4, 6, 8}. K=3 alone is listed as broken in
    -- V3's 4K needle test; K=4 works with rw=128 but is borderline
    -- (PARTIAL output drops characters); K=6 and K=8 are EXACT.
    key_bits: Integer = 4

    -- Value-tensor bit-width. [TONBI-V3] defaults to 2; attention-
    -- score-accuracy table shows K4/V2 + protected layers achieves
    -- cosine 0.9997 at 3.6x compression. V=2 alone without
    -- protected layers / residual window is in the MISS regime.
    value_bits: Integer = 2

    -- Codebook sizes derived from bits.
    key_codebook_size: Integer = 16  -- 2^key_bits at default 4
    value_codebook_size: Integer = 4 -- 2^value_bits at default 2
}

-- ============================================================
-- Open questions
-- ============================================================

open question "Key bit-width floor for symmetric configurations: [TONBI-V3] measurement shows K=3 alone breaks generation. Minimum-viable-K-bits may depend on model family and size. Default K=4 is tonbistudio's conservative choice; production deployments might go lower if combined with a larger residual window or layer-adaptive protection."

open question "Value bit-width floor: [TONBI-V3] default V=2 works only in combination with protected layers. Without protection, V=2 is in the MISS regime. Spec allows any value_bits ≥ 1; deployers must pair with turbo_kv_layer_adaptive or turbo_kv_residual_window to stay in the EXACT regime."

open question "Quality × compression Pareto frontier: [TONBI-V3] table gives point measurements at specific configurations. A full Pareto sweep across K ∈ {3, 4, 6, 8} × V ∈ {2, 3, 4} × rw ∈ {0, 64, 128, 256} × protected_layers ∈ {0, 2, 4, 8} has not been published at our target model sizes (Qwen3.5 9B, 35B-A3B)."

open question "Codebook asymmetry: should K and V use different codebook distributions (e.g. K optimised for query-matching, V optimised for mean reconstruction)? [PAPER] and [TONBI-V3] both use the same Lloyd-Max codebook family for both; the only difference is number of centroids. Open whether role-specific codebooks would improve quality further."

-- ============================================================
-- Composite rules
-- ============================================================

-- Key-tensor quantisation uses the key codebook at key_bits.
-- Composes with the core QuantizeHead rule from turbo-kv-4b /
-- turbo-kv-3b, parameterised by bits = config.key_bits.
rule QuantizeKeyHead {
    when: QuantizeKeyHead(tensor, seed)

    requires: tensor.count > 0

    let key_codebook = codebook_for_bits(config.key_bits)
    let block = QuantizeHead(tensor, seed, key_codebook, config.key_bits)

    ensures: QuantizedHead.created(
        norm: block.norm,
        inv_std: block.inv_std,
        indices: block.indices
    )
}

-- Value-tensor quantisation uses the value codebook at
-- value_bits. Same algorithmic structure as QuantizeKeyHead but
-- a different (typically smaller) codebook.
rule QuantizeValueHead {
    when: QuantizeValueHead(tensor, seed)

    requires: tensor.count > 0

    let value_codebook = codebook_for_bits(config.value_bits)
    let block = QuantizeHead(tensor, seed, value_codebook, config.value_bits)

    ensures: QuantizedHead.created(
        norm: block.norm,
        inv_std: block.inv_std,
        indices: block.indices
    )
}

-- ============================================================
-- Invariants
-- ============================================================

-- [TONBI-V3] ordering: keys should not be less precise than
-- values in attention-critical path. Formally we require
-- key_bits ≥ value_bits because the attention SCORE is
-- K-dominated (query-key match drives softmax shape); V only
-- influences the weighted sum after softmax has selected who
-- matters. Measurement support: K4/V2 works; K2/V4 has not been
-- measured to work.
invariant KeyBitsAtLeastValueBits {
    config.key_bits >= config.value_bits
}

-- Codebook sizes follow from bits.
invariant CodebookSizesConsistent {
    config.key_codebook_size = power_of_two(config.key_bits) and
    config.value_codebook_size = power_of_two(config.value_bits)
}

-- ============================================================
-- Implementation notes
-- ============================================================

-- Implementing asymmetric K/V in the llama.cpp port requires
-- either:
--
--   (a) Two ggml types — e.g. TURBO_K_4B for keys and
--       TURBO_V_2B for values. The attention op would need to
--       accept mixed types (currently FA assumes a single
--       KV type per head). This is the more invasive change.
--
--   (b) Per-tensor bit-width override on a single ggml type —
--       a field in the tensor metadata that tells the quantise
--       and dequantise kernels which codebook to use. Less
--       invasive but requires kernel-level dispatch on that
--       field.
--
-- [TONBI-V3]'s PyTorch approach corresponds roughly to (a): it
-- constructs two separate MSECompressor instances with
-- different bits for the key path and value path.
--
-- The [QUANT.CPP] authors have discussed asymmetric
-- configurations in project notes but have not yet shipped them.
-- Our llama.cpp port inherits the single-type limitation.
